defaultCycle journeys in London have increased by 176% on main roads in the past decade
default,
default and cycle commuting by Hackney residents now accounts for more than 15% of journeys
default –
default doubling
default in a decade.  
defaultYet even the capital, where cycle journeys 
defaultnow exceed 57
default0,000 per day, 
defaultstill has a low o
defaultverall share of cycling at a little more than 
default2% of all journeys, well below cities like 
defaultBerlin (
default15
default%) or Amsterdam (36%). 
defaultThe overall figure for
default the UK
default is
default 2% - significantly below the potential rate. 
default 
default&#xa0;
default1.2 
defaultThe key factor in deterring more people from cycling in the UK is road danger and perceived road danger. Recent surveys, both in London
default 
defaultand the UK, consistently show that a quarter, or more, o
defaultf the population would like to cycle or cycle more often. 
defaultS
defaulturveys carried out for LCC and British Cycling show that the number one factor deterring people from cycling is fear of road danger. 
default&#xa0;
default1.3 
defaultAs the 
defaultDfT
default funded programme of Cycling Demonstration towns
default has shown
default,
default cycling offers an exceptionally cost effective investment in the transport sector. 
defaultThe Cycling Demonstration Towns showed a cost/benefit ratio of £2- £3.5 for every pound spent and this is described as a conservative 
defaultestimate
default. 
defaultA cost
default/
defaultbenefit s
defaulttudy in Copenhagen (a city with high cycling levels) found that the total socio
default-
defaulteconomic cost of cycling (including travel time, health factors, pollution and congestion) 
defaultwas 0.60 DK
default (Danish Krone
default) per
default kilometre compared to 3.74 DK per kilometre for cars
default. 
default Cyclist fatality rates in Holland and Denmark compared to distance travelled are half those in the UK. 
default1.4 
defaultThe NICE (National Institute of Clinical Excellence) report on walking cycling, published in December 2012, makes clear that the health cost
defaults
default of an inactive population are enormous and comparable to those of smoking.
